Many =
great spiritual commentators, who are also founders of various sects within=
 hinduism have commented and written purports on the Gita. And each of thes=
e celebrated commentators have strongly disagreed with each other on variou=
s crucial points of interpretation of what the text says. Some have read it=
 to conclude that "X" yoga is better or higher than "Y" yoga, or A philosop=
hy is the right way to look at reality instead of Y philosophy, or interpre=
ted words/phrases in a sense that,sometimes does not make sense. And natura=
lly followers of each of these great Gurus believe that their interpretatio=
n is the final and maximum one.

Reading all this can be confusing. Rather =
IMHO the Gita looks more like a book of progressive arguments. Each section=
 builds up into the next. It is not one against the other, or one separate =
from the other. In that sense it is hardly a sectarian document, it does no=
t say one specific interpretation of the spiritual reality is higher or bet=
ter than another, but rather (probably because the reality is so complex)ac=
cepts that multiple views points are *simultaneously* true.



