Indeed, one can carv=
e one's own niche by combining multiple paths. They are not meant to be mut=
ually exclusive.
=C2=A0
I'll quote Swami Vivekananda from his book "Raja Yo=
ga" where he makes a comment on the 4 paths:
=C2=A0
"Each soul is potential=
ly divine. The goal is to manifest this divinity within by controlling
 nat=
ure: external and internal. Do this either by work or worship or psychic co=
ntrol, or philosophy - by one, or more, or all of these - and be free."
=C2=
=A0
Here are my 2 cents.
=C2=A0
Jnana yoga emphasizes on philosophization a=
nd wisdom. Karma yoga emphasizes on work and detachment. Raja yoga emphasiz=
es on self-control and self-mastery. Bhakti yoga emphasizes on devotion and=
 surrender to Supreme. One can pick whatever is natural to one and try to d=
evelop that quality. However, wisdom, detached action, self-control and sur=
render to the Supreme are not mutually exclusive. As one of these qualities=
 develops nicely in one, others will automatically develop too! Finally, a =
realized person (i.e. one in "Yoga" or oneness) will have all these qualiti=
es fully blossomed.
=C2=A0
Forget about horoscope, navamsa, vimsamsa, naksh=
atramsa etc. Irrespective of that, I strongly recommend against Raja yoga f=
or 99% of humanity. Even Ramakrishna advised
 against it. Controlling body =
and mind and forcing the psychic life force to purify and ascend requires s=
trict yama and niyama and clean nadis. In this age of polluted air, water a=
nd food, nadis accumulate great amounts of obstructions and Raja yoga can b=
e dangerous. This is not just my view, but what Ramakrishna explicitly taug=
ht in "Gospel of Ramakrishna" (one of the greatest spiritual texts IMHO). H=
e discouraged several of his sishyas from pursuing Raja Yoga. He taught it =
to Vivekananda, but did not encourage even him to practice it.
=C2=A0
Jnana=
 yoga is brilliant, but there is a distinct danger of falling into the delu=
sional trap of pseudo-wisdom. People of this age are not sincere/honest/sma=
rt enough for it. It is easy to delude that "all is Brahman. I am Brahman. =
Whatever I do, it's ok - it doesn't matter. It's all a delusion anyway" wit=
hout fully overcoming all innate conditioning that reinforces duality in co=
nsciousness every instant. Kind
 of like declaring wisely in a movie that "=
it's just a movie and not reality", but flinching in every scary scene, cry=
ing in every sad scene etc. Without absolute honesty, sincerely and earnest=
ness, jnana yoga can be problematic too. A long path of constant contemplat=
ion and self-correction can be reduced to a quick delusional jump to the en=
d.
=C2=A0
IMHo, for most people in this age, Bhakti yoga and Karma yoga are=
 the most suitable and safest.
=C2=A0
